revision.text:
'''Acatalepsy''' (from the [[Greek language|Greek]] α̉-, privative, and καταλαμβάνειν, to seize), in [[philosophy]], is [[Understanding|incomprehensibleness]], or the [[impossibility]] of [[Understanding|comprehending]] or conceiving a thing.<ref name="cyclopaedia">{{1728}}</ref> Acatalepsy is the incomprehensibility of all things. It is the [[antithesis]] of the [[Stoicism|Stoic]] doctrine of [[katalepsis]] or Apprehension.<ref name="lewes">[[George Henry Lewes]], 1863, ''The biographical history of philosophy'', Volume 1, page 297</ref> According to the Stoics, katalepsis was true perception, but to the [[Pyrrhonism|Pyrrhonists]] and [[academic skepticism|Academic Skeptics]], all perceptions were acataleptic, i.e. bore no conformity to the objects perceived, or, if they did bear any conformity, it could never be known.<ref name="lewes"/>
For the [[academic skepticism|Academic Skeptics]] acatalepsy meant that [[human knowledge]] never amounts to certainty, but only to [[probability]].<ref>acatalepsy. (n.d.) Webster's Revised Unabridged Dictionary. (1913). Retrieved February 16 2015</ref> For the [[Pyrrhonism|Pyrrhonists]] it meant that knowledge was limited to the appearances (phantasiai) and the pathē. The [[Pyrrhonism|Pyrrhonists]] attempted to show, while [[Academic skepticism|Academic skeptics]] asserted an absolute ''acatalepsia''; all human [[science]] or [[knowledge]], according to them, went no further than to appearances and verisimilitude.<ref name="cyclopaedia"/>
==Notes== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Concepts in epistemology]] [[Category:Skepticism]]
